Message from Mr. Melrose, at Algonac Jr./Sr. High School:

1. Even though we are sending all orientation documents out via mail today, we are still having physical orientations Monday and Tuesday (See Link Below) for anyone interested.

2.Students who have chosen virtual learning will be enrolled in the Edgenuity system toward the end of next week. Students will receive an email in their DISTRICT GOOGLE EMAIL ACCOUNT. That account and password will be in their orientation packet. Parents will also receive an email.

3.We will send out a communication early next week about the distribution of chromebooks to students who need them for virtual instruction. Pick up of devices will be either Thursday or Friday of next week.

post_text:
Message from Mr. Melrose:

Senior Muskrats and parents,

We will need seniors to be by the baseball fields at 5pm tomorrow to get lined up and ready to enter the stadium for graduation. Family or friends with tickets will be able to enter the stadium starting at 5pm. You must have a ticket. No tickets will be available tomorrow. Guests will need to sit in the home or visitor bleachers identified by tape. We will be practicing social distancing and ask that everyone bring a mask when social distancing will not be possible. The ceremony will start promptly at 6pm.

Graduation will be live streamed by Big Tilt and there will be a link on the district Facebook page. Student speeches have already been recorded and a link to those speeches will be on the school webpage.

We will provide an update around noon tomorrow in regards to weather and if any changes need to be made, we will let you know.

Thank you and we look forward to finally honoring our class of 2020!

image:

April 30 at 10:33 AM ·

Hi, friends. After discussing the situation with our community leaders, it was decided to provide another grocery giveaway for our community on May 9th. Many seniors and families are in significant need for supplemental food. Thanks to the Algonac and Pearl Beach Lions, Harsens Island Cattails, Community First Health Centers, Algonac Rotary, Woodside Bible Church, Zens family and many more silent donators for working together on this.

We now have enough food to help over 150+ families. How cool is that????

We have food pickup at the Algonac Lions Hall starting at 10:30. People will drive up and have the food boxes placed in their trunk. Gloves, masks, limited volunteers and careful social distancing will be carefully utilized.

We have tentatively scheduled 2 more for June 6th and June 20th. We are blessed to live in such an awesome community with such big hearts to help others. IT IS NOT TIME TO SURVIVE, BUT RATHER TIME TO THRIVE.

Please help us share the information with our community.

Principal Melrose

On Saturday, January 25, 2020, the Algonac Chapter of the National Honor Society helped the Women’s Life Chapter 883 hold a Mardi Gras Murder Mystery Fundraiser. Together they were able to raise a total of $2,320 for the National Honor Society's project of purchasing two (2) Refillable Water Stations for the school. Over 80 people from our community attended the event.

The Algonac National Honor Society would like to thank: Women's Life Chapter 883; CeCe and Company (a local design company) for offering their time and talent free of charge for the event; the Algonac Lions Club for letting the group use the hall free of charge and donating all the tips that they received from the cash bar; Neiman’s Catering for providing a delicious meal of New Orleans inspired flavor; and Women’s Life member, Laura Koehlmann, for providing her services free of charge!

Also, thank you to the staff members at the Algonac Jr./Sr. High School and the Algonac Robotics Club for their cash donations to this project.

Algonquin Student Council hosted a non-perishable food drive during the month of November. The students and staff at Algonquin collected 2,312 items, which were given to the local food pantry.

The class that brought in the most non-perishable food items was Mrs. Schuman's second grade class. As a reward for their efforts, the students won a classroom pizza party.

Thank you to all that participated. Your contributions will help many families.

This week the National Honor Society and the Junior National Honor Society inducted several of our Algonac Jr./Sr. High School students into their organizations.

On October 16, 2019, there were 27 high school students that were inducted into the Algonac chapter of the National Honor Society .

Then on October 17, 2019, there were 31 eighth grade students that were inducted into the Algonac chapter of the Junior National Honor Society.

Congratulations to all of the new members for their achievements.

post_text: Melissa Hanners and Brooklyn Lestage received the Patriot Award at the annual staff welcome back gathering. The Patiot Award is given for employer support of the Guard and Reserve. TSgt. Jeff Luts had nominated Mrs. Hanners and Mrs. Lestage for this award for their support when he was called to Active Duty last spring. The staff and students went above and beyond during this time, with a special send off and having sent several personalized packages to him during his deployment. He wished that he could have nominated many others.

Algonac Jr./Sr. High School senior, Andrew Catenacci, and eighth grader, David Clemons, qualified for the USATF Junior Olympics Nationals that took place in Sacramento, California, July 22-28, 2019.
>>>>>>> master

Andrew took 5th in his heat, and 31st place in the country, running a school-record time of 50.59 seconds in the 400 meter dash.

David competed in the 1500 meter and Javelin. In the 1500 meter he finished 15th in his heat, while running in temperatures over 100 degrees. He finished 5th in his flight in the Javelin, but was unable to make the finals in either event.

Thank you to those that graciously donated to help get these students to Sacramento, in which they represented Algonac so proudly.

This past weekend, Andrew Catenacci, David Clemons, Winter (Joe) Gunnells, and Taylor Reams, Algonac Jr./Sr. High Schools students, participated at the Regional USATF track meet at the University of Louisville in Kentucky. The competition included athletes that qualified from Michigan, Ohio, Kentucky, West Virginia and Indiana.

The National meet will be in Sacramento, California from July 22-28, 2019. Andrew Catenacci qualified in the 400 meter dash with a career-best time of 50.88. David Clemons qualified in three events: the Pentathlon, the 1500 meter with a time of 4:58, and the javelin with a throw of 24.16 meters. (David just learned to throw the javelin on June 20.)

Congratulations to our athletes.

post_text: Three of the four Algonac Robotics programs have earned a place at the FIRST World Championships in Detroit on April 25-27, 2019! Congratulations!
shared_text:
Sebastien Cournoyer‎FIRST Algonac Robotics
April 15, 2019 at 3:49 PM ·

I remember very clearly Tom Nader, the MC at our very first event describing a muskrats as a resilient little beast!!!!

Well, not only do we have a world class FTC team that was finalist at the Michigan FTC State Champ and qualified for the World Championship last December, we were fortunate enough to have one of our FLL Jr team being selected to attend as well!!!!

And i just got confirmation from FIRST in Manchester, NH..... the Algonac Full Metal Muskrats are going to join them at the FIRST World Championships in Detroit later this month!!!!!!!

We are in and we are going to have a blast!!!!

Algonac Community Schools – Community Update

According to the Michigan’s State Aid Act, all schools in Michigan must schedule and hold 180 days of school and 1,098 hours of instruction to receive full funding.
Many of you are aware that the district, along with most districts in the state, missed an unusual amount of school this winter due to inclement weather. For Algonac Community Schools the number of days missed was 10. The state forgives 6 days automatically, and also offers a waiver for an additional 3 days. ACS was granted the waiver, so in essence we have 9 out of the 10 days covered. So, the question is where do we add the required day?
After many discussions and careful… More

Algonac Community Schools Youth Theatre
January 14, 2019 at 10:29 PM ·

Spread the word! We are looking for singers and dancers to join our ensemble. We are continuing auditions in the chior room during seminar this week. Rehearsals start next week!

shared_text:
Lisa Clark‎FIRST Algonac Robotics
November 30, 2018 at 6:54 PM ·

Do you have a first-fourth grade child that is interested in joining Algonac Robotics? Are you interested in helping to Coach or Mentor an FLL Jr. or FLL Team. Please send an email to algonacfll@gmail.com. I am working to set up a meeting for parents interested in getting involved and one for students interested in FLL Jr. or FLL. Take a look at www.firstinspires.org for information about FIRST.

Note: FLL Jr. season will be August-December and FLL meets January-June and our competition season August-December.

Note: FLL Jr. season will be August-December and FLL meets January-June and our competition season August-December.

post_text: The Algonac Robotics Program was the winner of a $500 grant from the Community Foundation of St. Clair County for "Thankful Thursday". This was a result of support from our program's families, school staff and community members. The money received will help with costs that will be incurred at the State Championship. Thank you to everyone that made this possible.
